title: Calculating the ideal â€œSex and the Cityâ€ polycule! - Juan Pablo Sarmiento at !!Con 2024
description:
Calculating the Ideal â€œSex and the Cityâ€ Polycule!

Sex and the City, the iconic early 2000s show, depicted social life, sex, and relationships through a lens rarely seen at that time that shook society to its core. But this cultural phenomenon had one fatal flaw: it was based on the assumption that each protagonist could only end up with one person. I couldnâ€™t help but wonderâ€¦ what if each person could be in an ethically and consenting relationship with more than one person at a time? What would the ideal polycule be? How do we even calculate that? What would the math look like? These are the questions society needs to be asking! These are the real problems VCs should be investing in! Dare I say, if we put a man on the moon we can settle once and for all who Carrie actually should have ended up with. Itâ€™s time to disrupt polyamory.

Pablo is a full stack engineer, specializing in building software for humanitarian emergencies. In his spare time he enjoys contemplating hypothetical endings to TV shows and working out the answers to questions that should have never been asked.

Presented at !!Con 2024 (pronounced, of course, "bangbangcon"!) in Santa Cruz, CA -- https://bangbangcon.com/ 

!!Con is a production of the Exclamation Foundation -- https://exclamation.foundation/

title: 'Sex And The City' Fashion Collector Shows Off Her Incredible Closet
description: This month marks 15 years since the "Sex and the City" movie hit theaters, and no one is a bigger fan of the franchise than Dawn Anna Williamson! Over the years, she's amassed an impressive collection of Carrie Bradshaw's wardrobe. She opened up her New York closet doors to give Access Hollywood a peek!
tags: sex and the city,carrie bradshaw,fashion,style,Dawn Anna Williamson,sarah jessica parker

title: 'Sex And The City': See Kim Cattrall, Sarah Jessica Parker & More In 1998 Set Visit
description: Tuesday marks 25 years since "Sex and the City" premiered on HBO. In honor of the anniversary, Access Hollywood flashes back to our first time on set with the stars of the hit series â€“ Sarah Jessica Parker, Kim Cattrall, Kristin Davis and Cynthia Nixon â€“ in 1998. The actresses spoke about the importance of the revolutionary show, with Kim telling Access, "It's really giving voice to a subject that hasn't had a lot of voice in the past, which is women's sexuality." Season 2 of the "Sex and the City" sequel series "And Just Like Thatâ€¦" debuts on HBO and begins steaming on Max on June 22.
tags: sex and the city,and just like that,tv,sarah jessica parker,kim cattrall,interview,kristin davis,cynthia nixon

title: Costume Designer Patricia Field Shares 'Sex and The City' Fashion Secrets (EXCLUSIVE)
description: Sarah Jessica Parker and legendary costume designer Patricia Field were the forces behind Carrie Bradshaw's iconic style on "Sex and the City." Pat went on to curate looks for "The Devil Wears Prada" and "Emily in Paris." The fashion maven is detailing her rise to the top in her new memoir "Pat in the City." Access Hollywood producer and guest correspondent Emily Orozco exclusively met with Pat at her Patricia Field ARTFashion Gallery in New York City, where she spilled some style secrets â€“ including that she originally envisioned Carrie in a black dress for her and Big's wedding in the first "Sex and the City" film!
tags: patricia field,celebrity,style,sex and the city,carrie bradshaw,sarah jessica parker

ðŸŽ¥  More about this video: 
We've seen the clips and the clothes - Carrie Bradshaw from Sex and the City loves to live it up with regular nights out, fancy meals, cabs, and lots and lots of shopping. Her love for shoes is famous (or infamous?) and it makes you wonder: Could Carrie Bradshaw really afford this all? And if so, how? In this video, we do a deep dive into Carrie Bradshaw's finances, from her income as a writer to her expenses, net worth, and what she could work on. If you're interested in money management, growing wealth, or reflecting on your own finances - or if you'd just like to see all the wild ways Carrie Bradshaw lives - this video might just be for you :)

title: Sex and the City:  Eric's reaction to Charlotte's Condo
description:
*This clip is considered FAIR USE by Copyright Law*

Why do (some) people react this way when they see that someone is significantly better off than they are?  And note that by Charlotte's reaction she makes nothing of the difference, and it's meaningless to her.  (ie. she wasn't displaying a condescending attitude, etc)  So then why/how does being better off than some people somehow preclude you from being a candidate to them?

... then of course there are those to whom you are a candidate because you are better off, but that is a separate issue ...

The Clip:
Eric's reaction to Charlotte's Condo in Sex and the City, Season 4, Episode 18 (Season Finale), "I Heart NY"

title: Harvey Brownstone Interviews Candace Bushnell, Author, â€œSex and the Cityâ€
description:
Harvey Brownstone conducts an in-depth Interview with Candace Bushnell, Journalist, Producer, Author, â€œSex and the Cityâ€

About Harvey's guest:

Todayâ€™s guest, Candace Bushnell, is a best-selling novelist, journalist, TV producer, and, most recently, the star of her own one-woman show.  

Sheâ€™s the celebrated author of â€œSex and the Cityâ€, which formed the basis for the phenomenally successful TV show that aired for 6 seasons on HBO, followed by 2 hugely popular movies, and the re-boot TV series â€œAnd Just Like Thatâ€, currently in production for its third season.   

She has also written NINE other internationally bestselling books:  â€œFour Blondesâ€, â€œTrading Upâ€, â€œLipstick Jungleâ€, â€œOne Fifth Avenueâ€, â€œThe Carrie Diariesâ€, â€œSummer and the Cityâ€, â€œKilling Monicaâ€, â€œIs There Still Sex in the Cityâ€, and â€œRules for Being a Girlâ€.   Her books, â€œLipstick Jungleâ€ and â€œThe Carrie Diariesâ€ were BOTH made into TV series for two seasons.   

Back in the 90s, our guest had her own reality show called â€œSex, Lives and Video Clipsâ€.  Since then, she had an interview program on Sirius Satellite Radio called â€œSex, Success and Sensibilityâ€, which explored womenâ€™s careers and relationships.  She then had a 4-part web-series called â€œThe BROAD ROOMâ€, which took a humorous look at women in the workplace.  And THEN, she created her own BRILLIANT one-woman show called â€œTrue Tales of Sex, Success, and Sex and the City,â€ where she takes the audience on a whirlwind tour of New York City, from Studio 54 to the Lipstick Jungle and beyond, sharing her remarkable stories of fashion, literature and sex while pouring cosmos in Manolos.  This highly acclaimed show started out off-Broadway in New York and got rave reviews.  She has taken the show overseas, to a number of countries, and as far away as South Africa, and she is currently on tour in the US, playing to sold out audiences and getting standing ovations.   And in December, sheâ€™s taking the show to Australia.  She is the winner of the 2006 Matrix Award for books, and a recipient of the Albert Einstein Spirit of Achievement Award. Sheâ€™s a frequent guest on ALL of the major talk shows, and sheâ€™s constantly in demand because of her intelligence, warmth, wit, fearlessness and immense likeability.

title: "Sarah Jessica Parker's Unique 'Rabbit Rabbit' Superstition: A 25-Year Tradition for Good Luck"
description: Discover the enchanting world of superstitions with Sarah Jessica Parker's unique tradition of saying "rabbit rabbit" each month. For over 25 years, the Sex and the City star has embraced this quirky ritual as a way to invite good luck and positivity into her life. Learn about the origins of this superstition, its cultural significance, and how Parker's commitment to this endearing practice reflects the universal desire for hope and connection in our daily lives. Explore the charm of personal rituals and the magic of words that shape our experiences.

title: Senior Sex and the City
description:
Shaking off their frail and vulnerable image, New York Cityâ€™s older-aged singles are navigating dating and sex on a renewed quest for intimacy, after two years of isolation during the pandemic.

Subscribe to Journeyman here: http://www.youtube.com/subscription_center?add_user=journeymanpictures

According to the United States Census Bureau, New York City is home to 1.8 million people aged 60 years and over. More than 800,000 of them are currently unmarried. After two years in which Covid forced the strictest isolation imaginable, many are now joining younger singles in a post-vaccination dating boom. Eighty-six year old Hattie lives in midtown Manhattan; â€˜Iâ€™m bored! I want physical, I want interaction, I want to feel, I want to be felt!â€™, she says. As a single older woman, her opportunities for sex and intimacy were limited: â€˜because of the pandemic everything changed - because of illness, sickness, viruses. All of a sudden, the act of making love had so many cautions attached to itâ€™, she explains. â€˜Being in love and being intimate is something that I never really had. So before I die, Iâ€™d like to have thatâ€™, says 58-year-old singleton Mahendra.

description:
Mobile Phone Etiquettes | Tips For Modern Manners
By-Shajibur Rahman Khan

The People You Are With Take Precedence Over a Call 
If you are expecting an important call, tell the people you are with in advance. Otherwise, be respectful to those you are with, who have chosen to spend their precious time with you. 

Step Away From Others When Taking A Call 
Chatting away in public is impolite. Do not take calls in public places or around others. Find a secluded area or step outside to speak on the phone. That goes for restaurants, cafÃ©s, nail salons, and stores. If you are a passenger in a car, it is best to avoid taking a call unless it cannot be avoided. 

Do Not Use Speakerphone in Public Places 
Further to the above, definitely avoid using speakerphone unless you are somewhere private. Not only to protect the other personâ€™s privacy but as a courtesy to those around you. 

Consider Your Ringtone
The theme song to Sex and the City might be a fun ringtone for calls from your best friend, but you might be embarrassed if it goes off under the wrong circumstances! 

Know When to Switch to â€œSilentâ€ 
Switch to silent mode in shared public spaces where people are paying for an experience. This includes restaurants, movie theaters, and nail salons. This also goes for business meetings or anytime you are with clients. 

Avoid â€œCell Yellâ€
The tendency to speak with an â€œoutside voiceâ€ on the phone is a very real phenomenon. It is also poor cell phone etiquette! Keep your voice at a normal speaking level whenever possible. 

Cell Phone Use for Children
Many parents today offer their phones to children while in waiting rooms, in line, or at restaurants. Parents who had children prior to the smartphone are undoubtedly envious of this convenience! However, often when this device handover occurs, the phone is being used with the sound on. If you intend to let your children watch a video on your phone at the restaurant, make sure to be prepared with headphones so as not to disturb other diners who are paying for a nice evening out. This applies to any shared public space.

description:
S.E.X AND THE CITY 1998 Cast Then and Now 2022 How They Changed

S.e.x and the City is an American romantic comedy-drama television series created by Darren Star for HBO. It is an adaptation of Candace Bushnell's newspaper column and 1996 book anthology of the same name. The series premiered in the United States on June 6, 1998, and concluded on February 22, 2004, with 94 episodes broadcast over six seasons. Throughout its development, the series received contributions from various producers, screenwriters, and directors, principally Michael Patrick King.

title: Charlotte Gives Carrie Her Engagement Ring | Sex and the City | HBO Max
description:
When Carrie Bradshaw (Sarah Jessica Parker) needs money to save her apartment, she doesn't know who to ask. It's weird to ask her friends, things are complicated with Mr. Big (Chris Noth), and her job doesn't *quite* pay enough. Charlotte York (Kristin Davis), in the midst of a divorce, knows that the best decision for her is also the best decision for her friend. In a sweet moment, she offers her engagement ring to Carrie (as a loan, of course), just so she can get back on her feet and keep her apartment. After all, what are friends for?

CLIP DESCRIPTION:
As the gals enjoy a desert picnic, Rikard Spirit (Max Ryan) catches the lustful eye of Samantha (Kim Cattrall).

FILM DESCRIPTION:
The stars of the hit HBO series reunite with original writer/producer/director Michael Patrick King to deliver this sequel that finds the ladies venturing outside New York City for the adventure of a lifetime. Carrie (Sarah Jessica Parker), Charlotte (Kristin Davis), and Miranda (Cynthia Nixon) are all married now, but they're still up for a little fun in the sun. When Samantha (Kim Cattrall) gets the chance to visit one of the most extravagant vacation destinations on the planet and offers to bring them all along, they surmise that a women-only retreat may be the perfect excuse to eschew their responsibilities and remember what life was like before they decided to settle down.

The hit cable series Sex and the City catwalks its way onto the big screen in this feature-film continuation that fans all over have been clamoring for. Sarah Jessica Parker returns once again as Carrie Bradshaw, the style-maven journalist whose romantic exploits were the key focus of the show. Also reprising their roles are Kim Cattrall, Kristin Davis, and Cynthia Nixon, with the series' executive producer Michael Patrick King taking on writing and directing duties. Several years have passed since viewers last saw Carrie and company, though she's still involved with Mr. Big (Chris Noth) and completely consumed by her obsession for name-brand accessories. Meanwhile, Miranda is adjusting to married life and motherhood, Charlotte is still clinging to her dreams, and Samantha and handsome, steely eyed TV star Smith Jerrod (Jason Lewis) are now living together out in L.A. Of course, when the girls all come together, it's just like old times. Dreamgirls' Jennifer Hudson co-stars as Carrie's assistant.

title: Sex and the City Official Trailer
description: Sex and the City is coming to the big screen in a feature film adaptation of the hit HBO television series. The film will follow the continuing adventures of the series four main characters - Carrie, Samantha, Charlotte and Miranda - as they live their lives in Manhattan four years after the series ended. Stars Sarah Jessica Parker, Kim Cattrall, Kristin Davis, and Cynthia Nixon are all on board to reprise their roles, while the film will be written and directed by Michael Patrick King, who executive produced the original television series. Additionally, Chris Noth, David Eigenberg, Evan Handler and Jason Lewis will return as the women's love interests. Academy Award-winning actress Jennifer Hudson (Dreamgirls) has also joined the cast of the film and will play Carrie Bradshaw's assistant, a new character to be introduced in the film. Sex and the City is scheduled for a May 30th release.

title: Sex And The City Cast: Real-Life Romances Revealed! |â­ OSSA
description:
Embark on a thrilling journey into the lives of the Sex and the City cast! Can you believe it's been two decades since the show's last episode? Yet, our favorite stars continue to keep us intrigued.

Sarah Jessica Parker, slipping back into the role of Carrie Bradshaw in the spin-off "And Just Like That," reveals more than just her on-screen persona. She embraces aging gracefully, showing the world that beauty knows no bounds. 

Kristin Davis, our beloved Charlotte, isn't chasing marriage like her character. Instead, she's busy producing alongside her friends and enjoying her independence.

Cynthia Nixon, who played Miranda, celebrates her 12th anniversary with her wife, Christine Marinoni, showing us a different side of fame.

Kim Cattrall's absence from the reboot leaves fans curious, adding a dash of mystery to the mix.

Chris Noth, aka Mr. Big, faces some tough times, but he's holding steady with his family's support.

John Corbett, known as Aidan Shaw, still has that rugged charm. His relationship with actress and model Bo Derek has garnered attention and admiration. 

Join OSSA Channel as we dig into the lives of the Sex and the City stars. It's a journey full of surprises and secrets that'll keep you hooked!

title: Sex and the City (Theme Song) by Douglas J. Cuomo and Tom Findlay â€“ Charles Manning, Piano
description:
The â€œSex and the Cityâ€ theme music was written by Douglas J. Cuomo and Tom Findlay for the romantic comedy-drama television series of the same name.  Created by Darren Star for HBO, the series aired for six seasons, from 1998 to 2004, and starred Sarah Jessica Parker, Kim Cattrall, Kristin Davis, and Cynthia Nixon. Subsequently, two â€œSex and the Cityâ€ films were released, in 2008 and 2010. 

Creator Star had requested that composer Doug Cuomo write something sexy and sophisticated, with a Latin, cocktail-themed vibe. Cuomoâ€™s theme was exactly what Star wanted.  The famed main-title theme song was recorded near the Empire State Building with a bass player, drummer, saxophone player, percussionist, and pianist. The theme quickly became a popular ringtone for mobile phones. With a Latin, pizzazz-like style, pianist Charles Manning performs the â€œSex and the Cityâ€ theme song.

title: And Just Like That | The Big Funeral | [HD] | HBO Max | S01E02
description:
In this clip: Chris Noth, Sarah Jessica Parker, Evan Handler, Kristin Davis, Cynthia Nixon, David Eigenberg, Niall Cunningham,  Willie Garson (1964-2021), Mario Cantone, Julie Halston, Sara Ramirez and Molly Price (1:01).

About this clip: The recently-widowed Carrie Preston partakes in the funeral of her husband John in the presence of friends, family and co-workers. After a small speech made by his brother, we witness a montage-tribute, blending seamlessly with an elegiac eulogy. There's Gloria, Big's secretary, all tremulous. There's Che Diaz who offers a handkerchief to Gloria. There's Bitsy von Muffling who lost her husband, Bobby Fine to Covid in 2020. And then there's Susan Sharon who in her unmistakable voice expresses her distaste for Big's treatment of Carrie. The past, the present and the future converge in the musical funeral before Big's cremation.

title: SATC HD | The Jilting Scene | [HD]
description:
In this clip : Sarah Jessica Parker, Chris Noth, Kristin Davis ( gives you shivers at 4:06 onwards), Cynthia Nixon, Kim Cattrall, Mario Cantone, Willie Garson, Evan Handler, Lynn Cohen, Joseph Pupo and Alexandra Fong.     

About this clip: This is the most infamous scene in SATC narrative where we come to know of the impenetrable, phallogocentric Mr. Big's weakness (2:17 , 3:13 , 3:43). Not unlike a common man, he has his own share of jitters and lacks close male-companionship even for a momentous once-in-a-lifetime event like marriage. This scene fetches Big, big notoriety inasmuch sympathy. Carrie, all decked up in Vivienne Westwood and an avian head-gear, starts from the Goldenblatt residence at 930 Park Avenue, but cannot fly much high in the most important day for her life - the marrying of Carrie Bradshaw to John James Preston after years of trials, tribulations and Nijinskies. This event is what the preceding entire six seasons were aimed at and gravitated towards. In fact, this scene is the very "singularity" of the SATC "cosmos".  We see the white rose-petals fall down all over in the middle of the road, as the traffic witnesses their drama-unfold, like the broken, withered wings of a once-ambitious bird.

title: SATC | Samantha Jones vs None
description:
In this clip: Kim Victoria Cattrall (0:29, 1:10), Julia Sweeney and Amy von Freymann.

Clip Quote: " Samantha Jones: Excuse me, I don't know if this is an appropriate question to ask.
Nun: I think we passed appropriate a few seconds ago."

About this clip: In this deceptively funny scene, of the Catch-38 episode, written by Star, Bicks, Chupack, Bushnell, Tuccillo, and others, we are acquainted with the grim reality of breast cancer which, not unlike death, is the biggest leveler for all - ranging from the likes of Samantha Jones and some pushy people at Los Angeles and Miami, to those who cannot even avail the adequate medical care, much less an appointment with Doctor McAndrew. Samantha's "moral sentiments" necessitate that she uses Smith's name to squeeze in herself and the nun for an early appointment the following morning. 

The receptionist's apathy is the symptom of the privatization of medicare that plagues the American Dream; in fact American healthcare system is called out by Noam Chomsky as  based "overwhelmingly on virtually unregulated private health care"* which is "extremely inefficient and very costly"* leaving millions of people with "no insurance at all"* and insecure. To this end, he demands political support from the likes of Goldman Sachs and JP Morgan Chase in the aftermath of Obama's Affordable Care Act as also the plans during the Reagan years that didn't amount to anything substantial.    

This oncological scene highlights the unavailability of qualified doctors for all and sundry, which problem the Gubernatorial candidate, Cynthia Nixon, with her #MedicareForAll hoped to correct, tweeting thus, the last September:
https://twitter.com/CynthiaNixon/status/1037010847489556482

She also talked about her own mother's struggles with breast cancer: https://twitter.com/CynthiaNixon/status/1039213157770653696

When the A-listers in New York have to wait aeons for getting an appointment with a doctor, it's time we ponder on what the third world impatient patients go through! This excellently written tragicomedic scene, equating Claudius' speech post-regicide in Hamlet, "levels" the Catholic nun with a libertine PR-pro, the A-Lister with a mere receptionist and the privileged with the destitute!

title: SATC HD | The LOVE Scene | [HD]
description:
In this clip: Sarah Jessica Parker, Evan Handler, Jennifer Hudson and Chris Noth.
          
Dedicatee: Manolo Blahnik (b. 1942), Ludwig van Beethoven (1779-1827).        

About this clip: February "is wasted" at least 15 days in Manhattan. As NYC awaits the Spring of 2008, Rose blooms in Charlotte's arms. Harry Goldenblatt of Bloom & Goldenblatt fame, who once helped Charlotte settle for nothing less than a Park Avenue apartment as the alimony of the divorce settlement with Trey, now persuades Mrs. Goldenblatt's best friend, Ms. Bradshaw. Harry tries to reason with Carrie that Big cares for her. He further informs her that he's been writing to her, without receiving any reply in return.

While Carrie pretends to be unfazed hearing about Big's active interest in her, she cannot wait to get back to her apartment only to realize that LOVE is the secret password to her Assistant's file and LOVE, not hate, is the only way she can restore peace and harmony in her life.

Big beau's laconic billet-doux: "I know I screwed it up - but I will love you forever" to carrie@carriebradshaw.com stands out amongst the great love letters written by great men like Beethoven, Lord Byron and John Keats for their own great loves.

Finally, when the non-Parisian Saint Louise preaches the Gospel of LOVE to Carrie, the latter obeys her cardinal commands to return to her pre-war apartment at 1010 Fifth Avenue. It is here that she lets loose the reins of logic and runs towards her Big LOVE waiting for her with Manolos in his hands. She passionately kisses him in this scene of immense love and energy. 

We learn that, in her quest for the then $525 "Blue Satin Jewel Buckle Pumps", Carrie actually attains Nirvana and enters Real Estate Heaven. The Big Bard of passion and mirth, bearing uncanny resemblance to Lord Byron from (4:16) onwards, finally unites with his "La Belle Dame Sans Manolos", anticipating the enduring legacy of Beethoven's "Ever thine, Ever mine, Ever Ours*" eternal love of Sex and The City 2 movie.

title: S1E01 Clip | Power-hungry New York Women
And Just Like That | Carrie Stalks Natasha | HBO Max | S01E03 | [HD]
description:
In this clip: Kristin Davis, Richard Burton, Sarah Jessica Parker and Bridget Moynahan (1:01).
    
About this clip: After realizing that Natasha's bequeathed $1 million by Big's will, Carrie unexpectedly runs into Mrs. Natasha Naginsky Mills inside the all-gender restroom in a coffee-shop followed by a mild-altercation. The two wives of Mr. Big then extend sympathies/condolences to each other and offer coolness to their respective burns. The child-less Carrie learns that Natasha has two sons and is advised to un-follow each other on Instagram to keep it distanced.      

Carrie appears to have arrived at an understanding with Natasha - who is not interested in the money offered by Mr. Finance - after being stormed by the million dollar question, she tries to un-puzzle with her friends, earlier in the episode. Overall, this scene which takes a pacifying turn is still an iconic reminder of Natasha lecturing Carrie in S03E17 that she is a home-wrecker and husband-snatcher despite the newspaper-Dior-dress by John Galliano she's just strutted in:     

 "Yes. I'm sorry about it all. I'm sorry he moved to Paris and fell in love with me. I'm sorry that we ever got married. I'm sorry he cheated on me with you, and I'm sorry that I pretended to ignore it for as long as I did. I'm sorry I found you in my apartment, fell down the stairs and broke my tooth. I'm very sorry that after much painful dental surgery this tooth is still a different color than this tooth. Finally, I'm sorry that you felt the need to come down here. Not only have you ruined my marriage, you've ruined my lunch. I guess that's just what I had to say."

This Is How They Teach You How to Want It...The Slaughter: A Field Guide for the Hunted & the Hunter, The Dead-Alive, The Live-Dead Ones, The...Â is in direct communication with the ancient mythology of the wild hunt â€” Wilde Jagd , Wild Hunt or Chase in German â€” in which supernatural/ghost riders are pursuing a target. With elements that are poetic and prosaic infused with some parts field guide, some parts instruction and notes of the cautionary, this work poses big questions that erode the boundary between ourselves within our human skin suits and the natural world. How does identity â€” as animal or as human, within skin inheritance, within human intimacy, as gendered bodies, as predator or as prey â€” determine how and why we participate in the wild hunt? What happens when the hunter and the hunted change places? This Is How They Teach You How to Want It...The SlaughterÂ engages with a horror aesthetic that is sometimes as nuanced as the reminder of how we all witnessed Carrie Bradshaw telling Mr. Big to kill her over and over again in a Sex and the City episode to the raw details of what happens when one is caught by the hunter.Â What are the implications of race as it relates to who is prey and who is predator? This portal into the wild hunt provides another dimension for us to consider our relationship with nature and with each other.

title: What I would wear if I was the characters on Sex And The City #fashion #shorts #whattowear
Why Carrie Bradshaw is the Worst | Sex and the City (SATC)
description:
#sexandthecity #andjustlikethat

Do you like Sex and the City? Me too. But at the same time, I hate Sex and the City. Mostly because it constantly bombards me with evidence of why Carrie Bradshaw is the worst. So, before sequel series And Just Like That probably tries to rehabilitate our plucky heroines in the modern day, join me as I explore (apparently) funny Sex and the City moments featuring Carrie, Samantha, Miranda, Charlotte and Mr Big and indulge my crippling need for Sex and the City hate.

title: Sex and the City: How Carrie Was Wrong About Everything
description:
Sex and the City is one of the most beloved shows of its era, but we donâ€™t love it because its characters are always loveable. In fact, part of its enduring appeal is that it centers on four women who are flawed and frustrating and often get things wrong â€“ we enjoy watching them learn and grow on their journey. And at the middle of this imperfect quartet is narrator Carrie Bradshaw.

Sheâ€™s the main character who many love to hate, the kind of heroine that occasionally makes us throw stuff at the TV, because so many of her choices and attitudes are just plain wrong â€“ from the way she treats her friends and partners to her deep seated self-esteem issues that she was never quite ready to work on. So letâ€™s take a look at some of the things Carrie was totally wrong about (and how her willingness to keep trying despite her faults was her saving grace.)

title: Sex and the City - Carrie's Friends Aren't Real
description:
What if Miranda, Charlotte, Samantha arenâ€™t real, but just three parts of Carrieâ€™s psyche? On Sex and the City, Carrie Bradshawâ€™s (Sarah Jessica Parker) three best friends are presented as exaggerated archetypes of single women. Miranda (Cynthia Nixon) is the career-oriented cynic who preaches independence; Charlotte (Kristin Davis) is the old-fashioned romantic seeking a relationship; and Samantha (Kim Cattrall) is the sexually liberated commitment-phobic bachelorette. But if you look closer, you can also read the three secondary protagonists of â€œSex and the Cityâ€ as representing the three primary facets of a contemporary woman. title: Toxic Takeaways - What Sex and the City Got Wrong
description:
When Sex and the City first aired to 3.7 million viewers in 1998, the show was hailed as refreshingly candid and real in how it depicted love, sex, and being a woman in New York City, through the eyes of Carrie (Sarah Jessica Parker), Charlotte (Kristin Davis), Miranda (Cynthia Nixon), and Samantha (Kim Cattrall). But looking back, was it really so progressive? While it discussed sex with an admirable frankness, many of the insights it made and the conclusions it came to fell short. Too often it upheld regressive ideas about sexuality, and instead of breaking down barriers for everyone, it fostered problematic stereotypes around gender, race, and class. And so, as much as there is to love about this show, we canâ€™t help but wonder: what did Sex and the City get wrong?

title: Sex and the City 2 - OfficialÂ® Trailer [HD]
description:
Release Date: May 27, 2010

The fun, the friendship, the fashion: "Sex and the City 2" brings it all back and more as Carrie (Sarah Jessica Parker), Samantha (Kim Cattrall), Charlotte (Kristin Davis) and Miranda (Cynthia Nixon) take another bite out of The Big Apple--and beyond--carrying on with their busy lives and loves in a sequel that truly sparkles.

What happens after you say "I do?" Life is everything the ladies ever wished it to be, but it wouldn't be "Sex and the City" if life didn't hold a few more surprises...this time in the form of a glamorous, sun-drenched adventure that whisks the women away from New York to one of the most luxurious, exotic and vivid places on earth, where there's something mysterious around every corner. It's an escape that comes exactly at the right moment for the four friends, who are finding themselves in--and fighting against--the traditional roles of marriage, motherhood and more.

After all, sometimes you just have to get away with the girls.

title: Sex and The City: Miranda, Steve, and the Blue Moon
description:
This may not be to everyone's taste considering all of my other videos, but the revival of "Sex and The City" is so damn awful that I felt the need to try to remember just why I liked the original series to begin with. And it included Miranda and Steve. So, here is a scene I have not seen around on YT. This is more therapy for me in trying to forget the current mess, LOL! Sometimes, you CAN'T go home again. So, I'm trying to regain my former enthusiasm for SATC. 

Enjoy. Or skip if it isn't your thing. I understand.  :)   Especially since this will likely be my only SATC video as it is, again, sort of for my own sake. But if anyone enjoys, it's a bonus!
